This species is known from the tributaries of the Jordan River and from brooks and springs in the Golan Heights, where it inhabits streams of diverse sizes and current velocities (Figs 2A, E). Typical substrate in its habitats is composed mainly of pebbles and rocks of various sizes, as well as rich epilithic and submerged vegetation. Mature nymphs were collected mostly in spring (
March-May
), but also in fall (
October-November
).
